Timer / Cooldown System:
You will write self.timer -= dt a thousand times in a game jam for attack cooldowns,
invincibility frames, or delayed events.
A centralized timer system where you can just say
"Do this action in 2.5 seconds" will save you tons of debugging time.

2D Camera:
A system that handles translating world coordinates to screen coordinates.
You'll want it to support following a target (like the player),
clamping to map boundaries, and ideally,
a built-in "screen shake" function for instant game juice.

Sprite Sheet / Animation Controller:
A standard way to slice up a grid-based image and play animations by name
(e.g., play("run")), complete with frame-rate control and looping/one-shot settings.

Audio Manager:
A dedicated controller for music and sound effects.
You'll want the ability to crossfade music tracks,
easily play overlapping sound effects without cutting each other off,
and control global volume channels separately (Music Vol vs. SFX Vol).

Simple Particle Emitter:
Particles make every game look instantly better.
Having a generic class that can spew colored squares or small sprites
with randomized velocities, fading, and lifetimes is a game jam lifesaver.

Save/Load Utility:
A quick helper that serializes a dictionary into a JSON file and loads it back.
Great for saving high scores, settings, or level unlocks between sessions.